I love answering surveys like this because I so rarely get asked these kinds of questions about what motivates me to contribute to open-source and how I feel as a lead contributor. One thing I would mention for surveys like this is that you should separate out the idea of "developer community" (other technically proficient peers who work on, and contribute to, the project) and "user community" (non-technical or end-user consumers of your work), especially since my project is one that is heavily used by a very large non-technical audience. My answers reflect the much smaller developer community, while if I had the chance to answer the same questions about the broader user community, I would have brought up the verbal abuse, impatience, demands, and impoliteness of many of our end-users. Our inner circle of contributing developers, of course, has no such issues.

I'll admit that part of my current motivation is a sense of obligation to my users. Whether or not I'm personally interested in working on my project at any given time, I continue to maintain it because folks are relying on it. If I stopped working on it, there isn't any other developer ready/willing to step in.

One method of increasing code quality available in an open source project that's not always available to commercial/proprietary software is simply saying "no" when someone requests a feature. It's not a tool I've had to make use of frequently, but I have found that it can increase code quality by avoiding features that might be problematic from a quality perspective.
I changed jobs early last year. My new employer is less keen on open source, so my contributions have decreased in public code (but increased internally)

I am very focused on code quality. I use 5 different C compilers, with -Wall -Wextra build flags for development and very pedantic warning enabled before I release code. I use static analysis tools (clang scan-build, cppcheck) to check my code before release. I build and test my code on 32 and 64 bit, big endian and little endian systems. I use over 90 virtual machines to build and test my code using x86, i386, powerpc, arm64, arm32, sparc64, mips32, mips64, alpha, hppc, s390x, riscv targets to ensure the code works fine on a variety of architectures. I also build and test my code on Linux, BSD, Solaris, Minix, Haiku and POSIX based operating systems.  I also believe documentation should be the best possible to make the tools I write as useful as possible.
